name: 04- Model Training and Prediction
content:
Model Used

The chosen model for store segmentation is K-Means Clustering, an unsupervised learning algorithm that groups data points by minimizing within-cluster variance.

  • It works by iteratively assigning each data point to the nearest cluster centroid (using Euclidean distance) and updating the centroid position until convergence.
  • This method is effective for identifying natural store groupings based on purchasing and behavioral patterns.

Why K-Means?

  • Scales well with large retail datasets.
  • Produces interpretable and actionable clusters.
  • Flexible for testing different numbers of clusters (k) to capture business-relevant groupings.

Features Details

The following features were used to characterize stores for clustering:

  • Average Monthly Purchases: Captures spending behavior at the store level.
  • Invoice-Level Purchases: Average purchase amount per invoice.
  • Invoice Frequency: Average number of invoices per customer/store.
  • Product Variety: Number of unique products purchased.
  • Sales Distribution Across Clusters: Store representation in different customer clusters.

Feature Importance

While clustering models like K-Means don’t directly provide feature importance, we analyzed cluster profiles to determine which features differentiate clusters the most:

  • Average Monthly Purchase Amount and Average Invoice Purchase Amount were the strongest differentiators, highlighting revenue segmentation.
  • Invoice Frequency indicated store types with frequent but smaller transactions.
  • Product Count differentiated stores with broader versus narrower product baskets.

Model Metrics

To evaluate the clustering results, the following metrics and approaches were applied:

  • Silhouette Score: To measure cohesion and separation of clusters.
  • Cluster Distribution Analysis: To ensure clusters are balanced and meaningful.
  • Business Interpretability: Profiles of each cluster were assessed for practical business sense.



Clusters Distribution Analysis

The data clustered into three segments:

  • Cluster 0: Largest group (51.1%) – balanced, mid-level spenders.
  • Cluster 2: Second-largest group (40.3%) – frequent buyers with moderate invoice sizes.
  • Cluster 1: Smallest group (8.6%) – high-value customers, potentially corporate/wholesale.

Key Analytical Findings

  1. Average Monthly Purchase Analysis by Cluster
  • Cluster 1: Exceptionally high spending (~11M monthly).
  • Clusters 0 & 2: Much lower, ~1.5–2M monthly.
  • Interpretation: Cluster 1 contains high-value customers with significant revenue impact.

2.Average Invoice Purchase by Cluster

  • Cluster 1: Dominates (~6.3M average per invoice).
  • Cluster 0: ~1M average.
  • Cluster 2: ~800K average.
  • Interpretation: Cluster 1 focuses on fewer, very large purchases.

3.Average Invoice Count by Cluster

  • Cluster 2: Highest invoice frequency (~8.5 invoices).
  • Clusters 0 & 1: Moderate at 5.5–6 invoices.
  • Interpretation: Cluster 2 represents frequent, possibly smaller-ticket buyers.

4.Average Product Count by Cluster

  • Clusters 0 & 1: Higher product variety (~8.3 unique products).
  • Cluster 2: Lower variety (~7.1 unique products).
  • Interpretation: Cluster 2 customers are more focused on fewer products, while others diversify purchases.



Final Clusters

The segmentation resulted in three distinct clusters:

  • Cluster 0: Mid-level spenders, balanced purchasing patterns.
  • Cluster 1: High-value customers, fewer but very large purchases.
  • Cluster 2: Frequent buyers, smaller purchase sizes, lower product diversity.
